<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-632-865  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 632 865.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Nov 26 1990 v7 n47 p63(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM shows multiprocessing database. (IBM's OS/2 Database Manager)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Sherer, Paul M.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (Product development).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Product:   OS/2 Database Manager (Data base management system) (Usage).andO;Topic:     New TechniqueData base management systemsProduct DevelopmentMultiprocessing.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Paul M. ShererandM;At the recent Comdex/Fall trade show, IBM showed off how it might applymultiprocessing technology to bolster the performance and query capabilitiesof its OS/2 Database Manager.andM;IBM previewed four networked PS/2s running in parallel, each storing andprocessing one-quarter of a database table.andP;  A fifth PS/2 was used to parcelout queries between servers.andM;IBM also gave a glimpse of a modified version of OS/2 Database Manager thatoffers faster queries, the ability to process more queries per second andgreater storage capacities.andP;  The enhanced version ofandM;OS/2 Database Manager incorporated a module to direct queries to the properPS/2.andP;  IBM made no changes to OS/2 or any other OS/2 Extended Editioncomponent, IBM officials said.andP;  IBM also said it was working onfault-tolerence features that maintain copies of data on each of the serversfor protection in case a server failure occurs.andM;&quot;You're approaching mainframe technology on a micro,&quot; said Rick Romanelli, aprogrammer at IBM's Austin, Texas, facility.andM;Officials would not say when the technologies would surface in shippingproducts.andO;</TEXT></DOC>